description:
So far, we’ve been creating objects and then setting their fields by hand. C++ lets you run special code **automatically** when an object is created. That special function is called a **constructor**.

A constructor:

- has the same name as the class
- has **no return type** (not even `void`)
- runs automatically when you create an object

Example:

```cpp
class User {
public:
    std::string name;
    int userid;

    // constructor
    User(std::string n, int id) {
        name = n;
        userid = id;
    }
};
```

Now you can create a `User` like this:

```cpp
User u("Alice", 42); // calls the constructor
```

The constructor sets up the fields so the object starts in a valid state.

---

## Your task

CBit OS still uses the `Counter` class, but they want to make it easier to create.

Update the `Counter` class so that:

- It still has a **public** `int` field named `value`.
- It has a constructor that takes one `int` parameter and sets `value` to that number.

The tests in `main` will create two `Counter` objects with different starting values. Make sure your constructor sets `value` correctly.

starterCode:
#include <iostream>
// don't touch above this

class Counter {
public:
    int value;

    // add a constructor here
};

// don't touch below this
int main() {
    Counter a(5);
    Counter b(10);

    if (a.value != 5) {
        std::cout << "[FAIL] a.value should be 5\\n";
        return 0;
    }
    if (b.value != 10) {
        std::cout << "[FAIL] b.value should be 10\\n";
        return 0;
    }

    std::cout << "[PASS]\\n";
}
